                    <head>
                        <title>Euchologium Sinaiticum, new part (Euchologii Sinaitici pars nova)</title>
                        <origDate notBefore="1026" notAfter="1050">Approx. second quarter of the 11th c.</origDate>
                        <origPlace ref="https://www.geonames.org/732800/republic-of-bulgaria.html">Bulgaria</origPlace>
                        <origPlace ref="https://www.geonames.org/351820/jabal-musa.html">Sinai (St. Catherine’s or surroundings)</origPlace>
                        <note type="summary">Cod. Sin. slav. 1/N comprises 28 folios of the so-called Euchologium Sinaiticum. Two other fragments from the original manuscript are known: Cod. Sin. slav. 37 and St. Petersburg, Russian National Library, cod. Glag. 3 (Kondakov-folio).</note>                      
                    </head>
                    <msContents>
                        <textLang mainLang="chu"/>
                        <msItem>
                            <note>See detailed description in Tarnanidis 1988.</note>
                               </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="fragment">
                            <supportDesc material="perg">
                                <support>
                                    <material>Parchment</material>
                                </support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure type="leavesCount" quantity="28" unit="folio">28 ff.</measure>
                                    <dimensions type="leaf_current" unit="mm">
                                        <height>140</height>
                                        <width>111</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                                <collation>The folios were scattered and was gathered together based on handwriting, dimensions, and content. Only one quire, a quaternion, has survived intact. As there are many textual gaps, Tarnanidis could not sort and number all the folios according to the original sequence. He managed however to specify the position of most of the leaves within the original manuscript reconstructing it by using the other two known fragments - Cod. Sin. slav. 37 and St. Petersburg, Russian National Library, cod. Glag. 3 (Kondakov-folio). </collation>
                                <condition>Ff. 3, 13 and 20 are severely damaged; ff. 1, 2, 4, 11, 12, 18 and 21 are also damaged, but not to such an extent.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout writtenLines="24 26" columns="1">Written 24-26 long lines.
